I'd give this 3 and 1/2 folks if that were an option. It was a big hit and does not need to be modified very much. As others have said, the cake stands alone, so you can modify the glazes (try caramel) or have it without the chocolate glaze. I'd also recommend adding a few more nuts, but I am a pecan lover. Will make many more times.

Rating: 4
This cake served as an excellent birthday cake for a bourbon loving friend of mine. I followed the recipe exactly and had no trouble with it. I found the chocolate glaze to be wonderful but not necessary. This cake really could stand alone. It's rich, moist and has an scrumptiously smooth texture.

Rating: 4
To the inexperienced baker: you might have noticed this recipe is not like a usual cake recipe with more flour and less eggs. In fact this cake has many more eggs than a typical cake and almost no flour. It also has a great deal of real chocolate and not cocoa. This type of cake is called a 'flourless' cake despite it having a tablespoon of flour. It comes out more like a cheesecake in texture or truffle filling. It is a thin cake with a thinner glaze (or even just a dusting of cocoa or icing sugar) and you give each person a slice about an inch wide at the outside edge as it is very rich. There is no way to make a layer cake from a recipe like this. For that look for recipes with pictures of layers or even the word layer in the title. The two ingredients that make up most of the cake are the eggs and chocolate. To leave out the chocolate is to surely ruin the recipe. So if you're in the mood for a rich, dense cake with no airy bubbles, do try the recipe again exactly as it says. Flourless cakes really impress guests.

